article.headline: Huskers hurting even more now with Morse out
article.linkText: Short-handed Nebraska has enough to upset No. 25 Cincy
article.story:
LINCOLN, Neb. (AP) -- Alexa Johnson scored a career-high 27
points and had nine rebounds Sunday to lead Nebraska to a 65-55
victory over No. 25 Cincinnati.

	   Nebraska had only eight healthy players available for the game
and starting center Katie Morse tore her ACL with 8:10 to play and
is expected to miss the rest of the season. She had four points and
six rebounds.

	   The Huskers (5-2) limited Cincinnati to 30 percent shooting,
including 1-for-17 from behind the 3-point line. The Bearcats (4-2)
came into the game averaging 52 percent from the field and 44
percent beyond the arc.

	   Nebraska held Bearcats' leading scorer Valerie King to three
points, all on free throws. King, who had 33 points against
Nebraska last season in an 81-59 victory, was 0-for-14 from the
field Sunday, missing all seven of her 3-point attempts.

	   Cincinnati took an 8-0 lead, but Nebraska rallied to take a
15-14 lead on Shahidrah Roberts' jumper. The Huskers never trailed
again and led 26-23 at halftime.

	   Nebraska took its biggest lead at 48-37 on another basket by
Roberts. Cincinnati closed to 52-50 with 4:16 left before
Nebraska went on an 8-2 run over the next three minutes.

	   Margaret Richards had 12 points and nine rebounds for the
Huskers.

	   K.B. Sharp led Cincinnati with 20 points and 11 rebounds, while
Debbie Merrill added 18 points.

	   The victory was the 200th for first-year Nebraska coach Connie Yori.
She is 200-142 in 14 seasons, including stops at Creighton and
Division III Loras.
